eiro as much as inBuenos Aires were beginning to live off their pens as journalists and serial novelists, until the 1960s when writers of the quality of Clarice Lispector in Brazil and García Márquez in Colombia suddenly burst onto the world stage- is traced chronologically in six chapters which introduce the main writers in the main genres of poetry, prose, the novel, drama, and the essay. A final chapter evaluates the post-boom novel, testimonio, Latino and Brazuca literature, gay, Afro-Hispanic and Afro-Brazilian literature, along with the Novel of the New Millennium. This study also offers suggestions for further reading. STEPHEN M. HART is Professor of Hispanic Studies, UniversityCollege London, and Profesor Honorario, Universidad de San Marcos, Lima.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLatin American literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzLatin America. 0aSpanish American literaturexHistory and criticism. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  aChristopher Columbus.  aClarice Lispector.  aDrama.  aEssay.  aGabriel García Márquez.  aGarcía Márquez.  aLatin American Literature.  aLatin American literature.  aLiterary evolution.  aLiterary genres.  aLiterary works.  aMario Vargas Llosa.  aNovel.  aPoetry.  aPress.  aPrinted word.  aProse.  aReader.  aRepublic era.  aSpanish America.  aState.  aVaz de Caminha.  aWriter.  aliterary works.  aliterature evolution.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846155222?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846155222423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846155222/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer